---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "Learning";
const description = "How I trained my judgment through sustained study and applied practice.";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description}>
  <section class="section learning-hero" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <h1>Learning</h1>
    <p class="intro-lead">
      I follow where the questions get harder. Since 1992, I’ve returned to structured learning alongside my work. Not for credentials. For constraint. The goal has been consistent: sharpen how I make decisions under real conditions.
    </p>

    <div class="decision-grid" aria-label="Learning paths">
      <a class="decision-card" href="#formal-learning">
        <span>Formal Study</span>
        <p>Structured learning across Oklahoma State, Stanford, Stanford ICME, and MIT.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="decision-card" href="#field-learning">
        <span>Field Learning</span>
        <p>Observation and practice drawn from teams, users, civic systems, and real contexts.</p>
      </a>
      <a class="decision-card" href="#proof">
        <span>Work Translation</span>
        <p>How learning becomes judgment, interpretation, accountability, and system design.</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="formal-learning" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Formal Study</h2>
      <p>The throughline is not a transcript. It is a pattern of returning to structured environments when the questions required more precision.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="foundation-grid">
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Oklahoma State University</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">1992–1994</p>
        <p>Early study established the pattern. I was drawn to environments that forced clarity, even before I knew where it would lead.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Rigor of attending and completing work in a structured environment</li>
          <li>Foundations of computer science</li>
          <li>Discovered a love for writing that I didn’t fully pursue until 2025</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Stanford University</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2005</p>
        <p>I brought my team at Yahoo! into a course focused on improvisation. The objective wasn’t performance. It was collaboration: learning how to build on each other’s thinking, articulate ideas in motion, and design without shutting down possibility.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Listening to understand instead of listening to respond</li>
          <li>How to lift others up through words without shutting down conversation</li>
          <li>Actively helping others continue a line of thought</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Stanford ICME</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2016</p>
        <p>Coursework through the Institute for Computational and Mathematical Engineering (ICME) marked a deliberate turn toward data and systems. I focused on how decisions get made when information is incomplete, and how reasoning breaks under pressure.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Foundations of data science that shifted my career trajectory</li>
          <li>A deep interest in statistics and probability</li>
          <li>Introduction of Python and SQL into my working toolkit</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
      <article class="foundation-card">
        <h3>Massachusetts Institute of Technology</h3>
        <p class="entry-meta">2017–today</p>
        <p>Sustained study through MIT programs has focused on design, AI, and decision systems. This work has been self-directed and ongoing, built on repetition rather than milestones.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Design Thinking as an actionable, repeatable practice</li>
          <li>Strengthened leadership across enterprise and startup environments</li>
          <li>Applying analytics and AI to real decision systems where outcomes carry risk</li>
        </ul>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="field-learning" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>Learning in the Field</h2>
      <p>Some of the most useful learning happens outside a classroom, where behavior is visible and assumptions have nowhere elegant to hide.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="theme-grid">
      <article class="theme-card">
        <h3>
          <a href="/learning/evernote-research">Evernote</a>
        </h3>
        <p>We observed preschool children fingerpaint to understand how people explore color without constraint. This work, for the Skitch product at Evernote, informed how palettes could behave in a digital product, shifting from rigid selection to fluid exploration.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="theme-card">
        <h3>
          <a href="/learning/stanford-improv">Yahoo!</a>
        </h3>
        <p>Through improvisation training at Stanford, we practiced building on each other’s ideas in real time. This work supported frontdoor experiences including the Yahoo! homepage, MyYahoo!, and Yahoo360° at global scale. At the time, Yahoo! reached nearly a billion unique users each month, and our A/B tests ran against millions while touching only fractions of a percent of traffic. That context reshaped how I think about collaboration: systems should extend thinking, not shut it down.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="theme-card">
        <h3>
          <a href="/learning/civic-systems">Civic Systems</a>
        </h3>
        <p>Work within the Santa Clara County Registrar of Voters reinforced how systems behave under pressure. Procedures matter, but interpretation determines whether participation and trust hold.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="proof" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <div class="section-heading">
      <h2>How It Shows Up in the Work</h2>
      <p>Learning only matters here if it changes how decisions are designed, challenged, and made accountable.</p>
    </div>

    <article class="entry proof-entry">
      <h3>Separate signal from output</h3>
      <p>Applied in systems where outputs must be interpreted under real conditions.</p>
      <p class="entry-meta">Supporting post</p>
      <h4>
        <a href="/writing/when-ai-is-wrong-a-simple-operating-model-for-real-world-systems">
          When AI Is Wrong: A Simple Operating Model for Real-World Systems
        </a>
      </h4>
      <p>A practical operating model for separating signal, interpretation, escalation, and response when AI systems produce outputs that require human judgment.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="entry proof-entry">
      <h3>Design for interpretation</h3>
      <p>Applied where human judgment is designed into systems with ambiguity, escalation, and accountability.</p>
      <p class="entry-meta">Supporting post</p>
      <h4>
        <a href="/writing/designing-dignity">
          Designing Dignity
        </a>
      </h4>
      <p>A civic systems argument for rebuilding public infrastructure around human agency, interpretation, and dignity under real-world constraints.</p>
    </article>

    <article class="entry proof-entry">
      <h3>Stay accountable when wrong</h3>
      <p>Applied in systems that must remain legible, correctable, and trustworthy under pressure.</p>
      <p class="entry-meta">Supporting post</p>
      <h4>
        <a href="/writing/the-lineage-of-signal">
          The Lineage of Signal
        </a>
      </h4>
      <p>A reflection on the disciplines that make systems legible, durable, and accountable when interpretation carries consequence.</p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="section learning-close" data-pagefind-ignore>
    <p>
      I don’t use learning to expand what I know. I use it to reduce how often I’m wrong in systems that matter.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learning is still active. Today it meant explaining equatorial storms and jet streams to my six-year-old.
    </p>
  </section>

<style>

  .intro-lead {
    max-width: 42rem;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.58;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .decision-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: repeat(3, minmax(0, 1fr));
    gap: 14px;
    margin-top: 34px;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .decision-card {
    display: block;
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 18px;
    text-decoration: none;
    color: inherit;
    transition: border-color 0.2s ease, transform 0.2s ease;
  }

  .decision-card:hover,
  .decision-card:focus-visible {
    border-color: var(--text);
    transform: translateY(-2px);
  }

  .decision-card span {
    display: block;
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    line-height: 1;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 12px;
    font-weight: 600;
    white-space: nowrap;
  }

  .decision-card p {
    margin: 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.45;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .section-heading {
    margin-bottom: 44px;
  }

  .section-heading h2 {
    margin: 0 0 22px;
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.3;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--secondary);
  }

  .section-heading p {
    margin: 0 0 20px;
    max-width: 38rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .foundation-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 16px;
    max-width: 56rem;
  }

  .foundation-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .foundation-card h3 {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 4px;
    color: var(--title);
  }

  .foundation-card p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .foundation-card ul {
    margin: 12px 0 0;
    padding-left: 18px;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .foundation-card li {
    margin-bottom: 6px;
  }

  .theme-grid {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    gap: 16px;
  }

  .theme-card {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    padding: 20px;
  }

  .theme-card h3 {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    margin: 0 0 8px;
  }

  .theme-card h3 a {
    color: var(--title);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .theme-card h3 a:hover,
  .theme-card h3 a:focus-visible {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 0.14em;
  }

  .theme-card p {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text);
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .entry h3 {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 0 0 4px;
  }

  .proof-entry h4 {
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.35;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin: 4px 0 6px;
  }

  .proof-entry h4 a {
    color: var(--title);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .proof-entry h4 a:hover,
  .proof-entry h4 a:focus-visible {
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-underline-offset: 0.14em;
  }

  .proof-entry .entry-meta {
    margin-top: 14px;
  }

  .learning-close p:last-child {
    max-width: 42rem;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.5;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  @media (max-width: 760px) {
    .decision-grid {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
    }
  }
</style>
</Layout>
